\begin_layout Title
Discrimination in an Online Labor Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Sher Afghan Asad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model and Treatments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming risk neutrality, a worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ B,W\right\} $
\end_inset

 solves the following problem when working for an employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\left\{ B,W\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 denote the black or white race of an agent (employer or worker) respectively;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underbrace{max}_{e_{ij}\geq0}U_{ij}=\underbrace{max}_{e_{ij}\geq0}\left(F+(s_{i}+d_{ij}+p_{j})e_{ij}+\rho_{ij}\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})\sigma_{ij}(e_{ij})-c(e_{ij})\right)\label{eq:utility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the number of points (on a button-pressing task) scored by worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 when working for employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is the fixed money paid for participating in the experiment, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 (as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dellavigna2018"

\end_inset

) captures the sense of duty, norm, intrinsic motivation, and competitiveness
 of worker towards the task.
 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the the taste (like or dislike) of worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 towards the employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

's identity per unit of effort 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}$
\end_inset

 a' la 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Becker1957"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the piece rate chosen by the employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, we allow employers to select piece rate between 0 cents and 10 cents per
 100 points (in increments of 3 cents).
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ij}\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})\sigma_{ij}(e_{ij})$
\end_inset

 models reciprocity a' al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Falk2006"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the sensitivity of reciprocity by worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 towards employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})$
\end_inset

 is the kindness term that associates kindness perception to the piece rate
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

 by the worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 towards employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(e_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is the reciprocity term that capture the reciprocal response by worker
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 towards employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 given the kindness of the employer.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 These terms are defined as follows; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})=\underbrace{\left(F+(s_{i}+d_{ij}+p_{j})e_{ij}^{\prime\prime}-c(e_{ij}^{\prime\prime})\right)}_{\begin{array}{c}
\text{ }\text{Worker's belief about employer's }\\
\text{belief of worker's payoff.}
\end{array}}-\underbrace{\left((v-p_{j})e_{ij}^{\prime\prime}\right)}_{\begin{array}{c}
\text{Worker's belief about employer's}\\
\text{belief of employer's payoff. }
\end{array}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{ij}(e_{ij})=\underbrace{\left((v-p_{j})e_{ij}\right)}_{\text{Employer's payoff}}-\underbrace{\left((v-p_{j})e_{ij}^{\prime\prime}\right)}_{\begin{array}{c}
\text{Worker's belief about employer's}\\
\text{belief of employer's payoff. }
\end{array}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{ij}^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 denote the second order belief of worker about the effort i.e.
 worker's belief about employer's belief of worker's effort.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These beliefs can be elicited directly from workers by asking questions
 such as 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How many points do you think your employer expects you to score in this
 task?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 And to incentive such elicitation we can say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Your employer already revealed his/her guess of points that you will score,
 if your guess is within 100 points of the employer's guess, you will be
 paid extra 10 cents.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously, we will collect data on employer's belief from employer when
 they choose piece rate.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is the exogenous per unit return (value) to employer from worker's effort.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c(e_{ij})$
\end_inset

 is the cost of effort, which is assumed to be same for all workers 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 We assume the regularity conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $C'()>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C''()>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $lim_{e\rightarrow\infty}C'(e)=\infty.$
\end_inset

 Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dellavigna2018"

\end_inset

 we assume cost function to be a power function or exponential function
 i.e.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(e)=\frac{ke^{1+\gamma}}{1+\gamma}\label{eq:Power Cost Function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c(e)=\frac{kexp^{\gamma e}}{\gamma}\label{eq:Exponential Cost Function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These functions differ in their elasticity of effort with respect to the
 value of effort.
 Power cost function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Power Cost Function"

\end_inset

characterize a constant elasticity of effort given by 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\gamma$
\end_inset

 while exponential cost function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Exponential Cost Function"

\end_inset

 implies a decreasing elasticity as effort increases.
 Both functions requires the estimation of unknowns 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 which we will back out using observed effort at different piece rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:utility"

\end_inset

 leads to following solution (when interior); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{ij}^{\star}=c'^{-1}\left(s_{i}+d_{ij}+p_{j}+\rho_{ij}(v-p_{j})\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With power cost function this translates to; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{ij}^{\star}=\left(\frac{s_{i}+d_{ij}+p_{j}+\rho_{ij}(v-p_{j})\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})}{k}\right)^{1/\gamma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While exponential cost function lead to the solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{ij}^{\star}=\frac{1}{\gamma}log\left(\frac{s_{i}+d_{ij}+p_{j}+\rho_{ij}(v-p_{j})\zeta_{ij}(p_{j})}{k}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the above set-up, we design our treatments to be able to identify
 
\begin_inset Formula $k,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{ij}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 We make a simplifying assumption that the workers of type 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 are homogeneous given a treatment i.e.
 they will make the same effort choice in a given treatment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Baseline Treatment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We design baseline treatment to identify baseline parameters of the above
 model (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

).
 So to ensure that other parameter values are set to zero, we do following;
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) Employer's identity is not revealed to worker ensuring 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 there is no taste/distaste towards the employer's identity because the
 identity is not revealed, 2) Employer do not choose piece rate for worker
 rather piece rate is given exogenously to the worker ensuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

.
 This implied that the effort in this treatment is given as; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{ij}^{\star}=c'^{-1}\left(s_{i}+p_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This treatment will give us the baseline measure of effort of worker 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 for the given piece rate 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, the solution of effort has one behavioral unknown (
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

), and two unknowns from cost function (
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

).
 To back out these parameters we use effort corresponding to three different
 piece rates which gives us three equations to identify three parameters.
 Using 3 values for piece rate, we can exactly identify the 3 unknown parameters.
 These piece rates provide evidence on the responsiveness of effort to incentive
s for this particular task and hence allow us to estimate baseline parameters
 which will be used to estimate other behavioral parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Race Salient Treatments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the race salient treatment, workers will observe the race of the matched
 employer along with the selected piece rate and then work on a task.
 In the presence of group biases i.e.
 when workers derive different level of social preference for different
 employer's group then;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{ij}^{RS}=c'^{-1}\left(\left(s_{i}+\Delta s_{ij}^{p}\right)+p\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are implicitly assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}=s_{i}+\Delta s_{ij}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{ij}$
\end_inset

 can be separated into two components 1) 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

, which is independent of the employer type and include everything such
 as sense of duty, norm, intrinsic motivation, competitiveness of worker
 etc.
 and 2) 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta s_{ij}$
\end_inset

, which represents additional utility or dis-utility from working for the
 employer of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 which we interpret as taste towards the employer a' la 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Becker1957"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

