\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta s_{ij}^{RS}>0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta s_{ij}^{RS}<0\right)$
\end_inset

 will represent the increase (decrease) in effort because of taste of worker
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 towards (against) the employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta s_{ij}^{RS}<0$
\end_inset

 will be interpreted as the decrease in effort due to taste bias of worker
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 towards the opposite group employer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the difference in provided effort between the white employer
 and black employer 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(e_{iW}^{RS}-e_{iB}^{RS}\right)$
\end_inset

 for a given piece rate is construed as a difference which is only driven
 by the taste bias of the workers of group 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The main goal of this research is to identify the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta s_{ij}^{RS}$
\end_inset

 at different piece rates which we do in Section 6.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experiment Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of this study is to document the evidence of discrimination
 in the online labor market.
 We designed the experiment to allow for the possibility of discrimination
 in effort by workers towards the employers.
 Our experiment is carefully designed to ensure that observed difference
 in effort could only realize because of the taste bias of workers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Recruitment of Subjects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subjects for this experiment were recruited from an online labor market,
 Amazon's Mechanical Turk.
 Mechanical Turk is a crowd-sourcing web-service that allows employers (called
 requester) to get tasks (called Human Intelligence Tasks (HITs)) executed
 by employees (called workers) in exchange for a wage (called reward).
 Mechanical Turk is a widely used platform in research in economics and
 give access to large pool of applicants at a much affordable rate hence
 allowing for the well powered study.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Paolacci2010"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Paolacci2014"

\end_inset

 for discussion on demographic characteristics and representation of subjects
 from Mechanical Turk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recruit subjects we posted the screen-er survey as the HIT on Mechanical
 Turk with the following description 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fill out this 2-minutes screener survey to qualify for the immediate second
 study (that study will take ~15 minutes and pay 1 dollar plus bonus).
 You MUST use your webcam and take a picture (following guidelines) to be
 considered for the study.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\emph default
The screen-er survey is given in the Appendix A.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on the responses in the screen-er survey, we invited participants
 above the age of 18 who reported their race as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Black or African American
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

White or Caucasian
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to participate in the experiment.
 Everyone else was shown the exit screen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since our choice of task is same as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dellavigna2018"

\end_inset

, we can use results from their study to determine the sample size that
 can achieve sufficient power for our study.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dellavigna2018"

\end_inset

 found that the points scored in each treatment have a standard deviation
 of around 660 points.
 Assuming this standard deviation for each treatment and assuming a minimum
 detectable effect of 185 points between two treatments, we will need around
 200 observations in each sub-treatment to have a power of 80 percent.
 This implies that we will need 200 x 12= 2,400 observations in total for
 all 12 sub-treatments.
 In our design one observation constitute two subjects - one employer and
 one worker - therefore we need to recruit around 400 subjects in each treatment
 implying a total sample of size 4,800.
 These calculations are obviously for the full study, and they assume that
 we have control on the number of subjects in each treatment.
 As we learned from the pilot, we need to recruit 10 white employers to
 find one black employer and thus these sub-treatments are not going to
 have balanced sample sizes.
 In the light of this, we will be revising our design for the full study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Task
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We designed this experiment to observe whether workers discriminate in their
 effort when working for different employer types and then to back out the
 behavioral parameter of distaste.
 For this purpose we needed a task which is costly to workers.
 We settled on a button-pressing task as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dellavigna2018"

\end_inset

.
 The task involves alternating presses of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

b
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on keyboard for 10 minutes.
 We settled on this task because it is simple to understand and have features
 that parallel clerical jobs: it involves repetition and it gets tiring,
 thus testing the motivation of the workers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Experiment Flow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiment proceeded as follows: (1) HIT was posted on Mechanical Turk
 for a screen-er survey, (2) subjects were presented with the consent form,
 (3) those who consented and met the criteria were shown a screen to initiate
 the experiment, (4) upon initiation a subject was randomly assigned to
 one of the treatment groups and then to the role of employer or worker.
 The first person to initiate the experiment was always assigned the role
 of employer while the second person was made the worker.
 One employer and one worker formed a group for this experiment.
 The flow of the screenshots of the screens that subjects saw are given
 in Appendix A.
